04994nam a22006615i 9780520919112DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19961996cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209191127 a10.1525/97805209191122doi  a(DE-B1597)648283  a(OCoLC)1414457534  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aMUS0150002bisacsh04a780/.8968729507471qOCoLC220/eng/202311201 aGlasser, Ruth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMy Music Is My Flag :bPuerto Rican Musicians and Their New York Communities, 1917-1940 /cRuth Glasser; ed. by Ruth Glasser. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1996] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin American Studies Center, UCLA00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. "In Our House, Music Was Eaten for Breakfast" -- t2. From "Indianola" to "No Cola" The Strange Career of the Afro-Puerto Rican Musician -- t3. Pipe Wrenches and Valve Trombones Puerto Rican Worker-Musicians -- t4. "Vente Tu" Puerto Rican Musicians and the Recording Industry -- t5. "El Home Relief" Canario and the New York Plena -- tConclusion: Son de Borinquen, Son del Barrio -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPuerto Rican music in New York is given center stage in Ruth Glasser's original and lucid study. Exploring the relationship between the social history and forms of cultural expression of Puerto Ricans, she focuses on the years between the two world wars. Her material integrates the experiences of the mostly working-class Puerto Rican musicians who struggled to make a living during this period with those of their compatriots and the other ethnic groups with whom they shared the cultural landscape.Through recorded songs and live performances, Puerto Rican musicians were important representatives for the national consciousness of their compatriots on both sides of the ocean. Yet they also played with African-American and white jazz bands, Filipino or Italian-American orchestras, and with other Latinos. Glasser provides an understanding of the way musical subcultures could exist side by side or even as a part of the mainstream, and she demonstrates the complexities of cultural nationalism and cultural authenticity within the very practical realm of commercial music.Illuminating a neglected epoch of Puerto Rican life in America, Glasser shows how ethnic groups settling in the United States had choices that extended beyond either maintenance of their homeland traditions or assimilation into the dominant culture. Her knowledge of musical styles and performance enriches her analysis, and a discography offers a helpful addition to the text.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPopular musicxHistory and criticismxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aPopular musicxHistory and criticismxPuerto Rico. 0aPopular musiczNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory and criticism. 0aPopular musiczPuerto RicoxHistory and criticism. 0aPuerto RicansxEthnic identityxNew York (State)xNew YorkxNew York (State)xNew YorkxPuerto Rico. 0aPuerto RicansxMusicxHistory and criticismxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aPuerto RicanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxEthnic identity. 0aPuerto RicanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxMusicxHistory and criticism. 4aEthnomusicology. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Ethnomusicology.2bisacsh1 aAmbiente, Buscando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlasser, Ruth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package 